# TypeScript Guidelines

## Public API

- All exports have explicit types (params + return).
- Generic params have constraints + descriptive names (`TArgs`, `TResult` — not `A`, `R`).
- Prefer `type` over `interface`. No `I` prefix, no `Type` suffix.

```typescript
// ✅
export class ObservableValue<T> {
  constructor(private value: T) {}
  public getValue(): T { return this.value }
}

// ❌ implicit return type, single-letter generic
export function createInjector(options) { return new Injector(options) }
```

## NO `any` — one exception

`any` forbidden in values, params, return types. **Exception:** generic constraint position when variance breaks `unknown` inference (e.g. callback param positions).

```typescript
// ✅ unknown for truly unknown
const process = (data: unknown): string =>
  typeof data === 'string' ? data : JSON.stringify(data)

// ✅ any only allowed in constraint position
type ExtractPaths<T extends Record<string, NestedRoute<any>>> = { /* ... */ }

// ❌ any anywhere else
export function process(data: any): string { return data.toString() }
```

Alternatives: `unknown` + type guard, generics, union types, utility types.

`@typescript-eslint/no-explicit-any` is **disabled** in `eslint.config.js` because the rule has no option for the constraint-position exception. Reviewers enforce the rule in code review.

## Inference

Let TS infer internally. Be explicit at API boundaries, complex switch/case branches, or when inference is ambiguous.

```typescript
// ✅ inferred internally
const users = ['Alice', 'Bob']
const count = users.length

// ✅ explicit at exports
export function get<T>(token: Token<T>): T { /* ... */ }

// ❌ noisy
const count: number = 5
```

## Type guards

Provide guards for runtime checks. Use them, not type assertions.

```typescript
// ✅
export const isObservableValue = <T>(value: unknown): value is ObservableValue<T> =>
  value instanceof ObservableValue

const isNonNullable = <T>(value: T | null | undefined): value is T =>
  value !== null && value !== undefined

users.filter(isNonNullable) // type-narrowed
```

## Discriminated unions

For multi-state values. Always include a `status` / `kind` discriminator.

```typescript
// ✅
type CacheState<T> =
  | { status: 'idle' }
  | { status: 'loading' }
  | { status: 'loaded'; value: T }
  | { status: 'error'; error: string }

// ❌ no discriminator → cannot narrow
type Bad<T> = { loading: boolean; error?: string; data?: T }
```

## Assertions

Avoid. Use type guards or `as const` instead.

```typescript
// ✅ as const for literal types
const colors = ['red', 'green', 'blue'] as const
type Color = (typeof colors)[number]

// ✅ assertion only when DOM API leaves no choice
const el = document.getElementById('x') as HTMLInputElement | null

// ❌ dangerous
const user = unknownValue as User       // prefer guard
const x = maybe!                        // prefer optional chaining
```

Avoid `!` non-null assertion. Prefer `?.` and `??`.

## Utility types

Reuse built-ins (`Partial`, `Pick`, `Omit`, `Record`, `Required`, `Readonly`). Export project-specific helpers when reused 2+ times.

## Double-cast anti-pattern

Never `as unknown as T`. If you need a cast that strong, you're missing a type guard or a generic. Refactor.

## Checklist (public API)

- [ ] No `any` (except generic constraint exception)
- [ ] Explicit types on all exports
- [ ] Generic params named & constrained
- [ ] Type guards for runtime checks
- [ ] Discriminated unions for multi-state
- [ ] No `as unknown as T`, no `!` non-null

Tools: `yarn build` (`tsc -b packages`), strict mode is on.
